 Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1438–1499":"circa 1438–1499","1438–1499":"1438–1499","1430–1497":"1430–1497","1455–1525":"1455–1525","1455–Female":"1455–Overleden","1466–1513":"1466–1513","1491–1548":"1491–1548","1400–1452":"1400–1452","1409–1449":"1409–1449","ABT 1455":"circa 1455","1491":"1491","ABT 1491":"circa 1491","1525":"1525","1513":"1513","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1499":"1499","1400":"1400","about 1438":"circa 1438","1497":"1497","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1429":"1429","1449":"1449","1548":"1548","1438":"1438","Long Stratton, Norfolk, England":"Long Stratton, Norfolk, England","Blackford, Norfolk, England":"Blackford, Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Holt, Norfolk, England":"Holt, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"about 1438–1499":"about 1438–1499","1438–1499":"1438–1499","1430–1497":"1430–1497","1455–1525":"1455–1525","1455–Female":"1455–Deceased","1466–1513":"1466–1513","1491–1548":"1491–1548","1400–1452":"1400–1452","1409–1449":"1409–1449","ABT 1455":"about 1455","1491":"1491","ABT 1491":"about 1491","1525":"1525","1513":"1513","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1499":"1499","1400":"1400","about 1438":"about 1438","1497":"1497","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1429":"1429","1449":"1449","1548":"1548","1438":"1438","Long Stratton, Norfolk, England":"Long Stratton, Norfolk, England","Blackford, Norfolk, England":"Blackford, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Holt, Norfolk, England":"Holt, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":17,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Billingford was born about 1438, in Long Stratton, Norfolk, England, her father, William Billingford, was 39 and her mother, Aleyn Harple, was 30. She married James Gresham in 1456, in Long Stratton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1499, in her hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"about 1438–1499":"umbes 1438–1499","1438–1499":"1438–1499","1430–1497":"1430–1497","1455–1525":"1455–1525